{"type":"message","id":"ab9a2e13","parentId":"303aabef","timestamp":"2026-07-11T13:13:50.588Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_d48e83c3960d41a3acb1a106","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\ndate: 2026-07-11\nn: 1\npillar: Technology & AI innovations\nsource: https://venturebeat.com/technology/openai-introduces-chatgpt-work-a-cloud-based-ai-agent-that-manages-tasks-across-email-slack-and-calendars\nsource_date: 2026-07-10\nstatus: pending\n---\n\n𝗬𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗔𝗜 𝗮𝘀𝘀𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗮𝗻𝘁 𝗷𝘂𝘀𝘁 𝗴𝗼𝘁 𝗮 𝗽𝗿𝗼𝗺𝗼𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻. 𝗔𝗿𝗲 𝘆𝗼𝘂 𝗿𝗲𝗮𝗱𝘆?\n\nChatGPT Work launched yesterday. It's not a chatbot anymore — it's a cloud-based AI agent that runs 24/7, connects to your email, Slack, calendar, and GitHub, and completes multi-step projects while you sleep.\n\nPowered by GPT-5.6. Available to all Plus users at $20/month.\n\nHere's what changed:\n→ It lives in the cloud, not your laptop\n→ It schedules meetings, writes docs, builds websites\n→ It works for hours on complex tasks without you driving each step\n\nThe old way: You prompt → AI answers → You copy/paste → Repeat\nThe new way: You describe the outcome → AI delivers the finished work\n\nThis is the shift from \"AI helps me write\" to \"AI does the work.\"\n\nOpenAI just made autonomous agents accessible to 50 million paying subscribers overnight. Your competitors now have a junior employee who never sleeps, never complains, and costs $240/year.\n\nWhat's your plan for an AI workforce?\n\n#AI #AIAgents #FutureOfWork #GPT56 #Automation\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1783775630583}}
{"type":"message","id":"a2b65919","parentId":"ab9a2e13","timestamp":"2026-07-11T13:13:50.596Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_3f70b175bbf0439897b3d134","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\ndate: 2026-07-11\nn: 2\npillar: Technology & AI innovations\nsource: https://venturebeat.com/orchestration/wall-street-is-debating-the-ai-buildout-enterprises-just-answered-86-say-their-gpus-run-at-half-capacity-or-less\nsource_date: 2026-07-10\nstatus: pending\n---\n\n𝗬𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗚𝗣𝗨𝘀 𝗮𝗿𝗲 𝗮𝘁 𝗵𝗮𝗹𝗳 𝗰𝗮𝗽𝗮𝗰𝗶𝘁𝘆. 𝗬𝗼𝘂'𝗿𝗲 𝗯𝗶𝗹𝗹𝗲𝗱 𝗳𝗼𝗿 𝗳𝘂𝗹𝗹.\n\nNew research from 573 enterprise leaders: 86% of companies running their own GPUs report utilization at 50% or less.\n\nThat's the most expensive hardware in your building sitting half-empty while the invoice stays full.\n\nThe measurement gap makes it worse:\n→ Only 44% rigorously track what their AI compute costs and returns\n→ The rest are estimating — or guessing\n\nMeanwhile 54% had an AI agent security incident or near-miss in the past year. And 71% admit most of their \"agents\" are single-prompt chatbots in trenchcoats — not autonomous multi-step workers.\n\nThe pattern: Enterprises deployed agents first. Controls came later. Now they're retrofitting.\n\nThree moves that matter right now:\n1. Measure GPU utilization before buying more compute\n2. Give every agent its own scoped identity\n3. Govern the business definitions your agents read from\n\nDon't buy another GPU until you know what the ones you have are actually doing.\n\n#AI #EnterpriseAI #GPU #CloudComputing #AIOps\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1783775630593}}
{"type":"message","id":"927c5643","parentId":"a2b65919","timestamp":"2026-07-11T13:13:50.602Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_103c0ae35df544e8a373e27e","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\ndate: 2026-07-11\nn: 3\npillar: Technology & AI innovations\nsource: https://venturebeat.com/orchestration/enterprise-ai-is-entering-an-evaluation-gap-agents-are-gaining-autonomy-faster-than-companies-can-verify-them\nsource_date: 2026-07-10\nstatus: pending\n---\n\n𝗛𝗮𝗹𝗳 𝗼𝗳 𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗲𝗿𝗽𝗿𝗶𝘀𝗲𝘀 𝘀𝗵𝗶𝗽𝗽𝗲𝗱 𝗮𝗻 𝗔𝗜 𝗮𝗴𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝘁𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝗽𝗮𝘀𝘀𝗲𝗱 𝗮𝗹𝗹 𝘁𝗲𝘀𝘁𝘀 — 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗳𝗮𝗶𝗹𝗲𝗱 𝗰𝘂𝘀𝘁𝗼𝗺𝗲𝗿𝘀.\n\nThe evaluation gap is real: AI agents are gaining autonomy faster than companies can verify them.\n\nThe data:\n→ 66% allow production deployment without human review — or are building toward it\n→ Only 5% fully trust the automated evaluations making those decisions\n→ 29% say the #1 weakness is poor alignment with real-world outcomes\n\nHere's the trap: A passing test doesn't mean a working agent. It means the agent succeeded once. It doesn't mean it succeeds every time.\n\nThe fix isn't slowing down. It's testing differently:\n→ Run the same scenario multiple times\n→ Vary phrasing and context\n→ Inject tool failures\n→ Turn every production incident into a permanent regression test\n\nRepeatability is the metric that matters. Not capability — consistency.\n\nYour agent can do the job once. Can it do it a thousand times without breaking?\n\n#AI #AIAgents #Testing #EnterpriseAI #Reliability\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1783775630600}}
